In the `Update` method, we first retrieve the position and rotation data from the headset and controllers. We then use inverse kinematics to estimate the position of the feet, which allows us to estimate the position of the hips as the midpoint between the two feet. Finally, we rotate the hips based on the headset rotation to ensure that they are facing in the correct direction.

Note that this script only provides an approximate estimate of the position of the hips based on the available data. Depending on the specific game or application you are building, you may need to use additional techniques to further refine the estimated position of the hips.

Thanks for clarifying the additional requirements. Here's an updated C# script that takes into account the position and rotation of both the headset and controllers to estimate the rotation of the player's hips. It also includes logic to detect when the player is bowing and adjust the hip position accordingly:


```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class HipTracker : MonoBehaviour
{
 public Transform headset;
 public Transform leftController;
 public Transform rightController;
 public Transform hips;

 public float bowAngleThreshold = 45f;
 public float bowHipOffset = 0.2f;

 private Animator animator;
 private bool isBowing;

 void Start()
 {
 animator = GetComponent<Animator>();
 }

 void Update()
 {
 Vector3 leftHandPos = leftController.position;
 Vector3 rightHandPos = rightController.position;
 Vector3 headPos = headset.position;
 Quaternion leftHandRot = leftController.rotation;
 Quaternion rightHandRot = rightController.rotation;
 Quaternion headRot = headset.rotation;

 // Use inverse kinematics to estimate the position of the hips
 animator.SetIKPositionWeight(AvatarIKGoal.LeftFoot, 1);
 animator.SetIKPositionWeight(AvatarIKGoal.RightFoot, 1);
 animator.SetIKRotationWeight(AvatarIKGoal.LeftFoot, 1);
 animator.SetIKRotationWeight(AvatarIKGoal.RightFoot, 1);
 animator.SetIKHintPositionWeight(AvatarIKHint.LeftKnee, 1);
 animator.SetIKHintPositionWeight(AvatarIKHint.RightKnee, 1);

 Vector3 leftFootPos = animator.GetIKPosition(AvatarIKGoal.LeftFoot);
 Vector3 rightFootPos = animator.GetIKPosition(AvatarIKGoal.RightFoot);
 Quaternion leftFootRot = animator.GetIKRotation(AvatarIKGoal.LeftFoot);
 Quaternion rightFootRot = animator.GetIKRotation(AvatarIKGoal.RightFoot);

 Vector3 hipsPos = (leftFootPos + rightFootPos) / 2f;

 // Determine the forward direction of the hips
 Vector3 headForward = headRot * Vector3.forward;
 Vector3 headUp = headRot * Vector3.up;
 Vector3 controllerForward = (leftHandRot * Vector3.forward + rightHandRot * Vector3.forward) / 2f;
 Vector3 hipsForward = (headForward + controllerForward).normalized;
 Vector3 hipsUp = (headUp + Vector3.up) / 2f;
 hips.rotation = Quaternion.LookRotation(hipsForward, hipsUp);

 // Adjust hip position if player is bowing
 float angle = Vector3.Angle(headForward, Vector3.down);
 if (angle > bowAngleThreshold && !isBowing)
 {
 isBowing = true;
 hipsPos -= hipsForward * bowHipOffset;
 }
 else if (angle <= bowAngleThreshold && isBowing)
 {
 isBowing = false;
 hipsPos += hipsForward * bowHipOffset;
 }

 hips.position = hipsPos;
 }
}
```
In this updated script, we calculate the forward direction of the hips as the average of the forward direction of the headset and the controllers. We also calculate the up direction of the hips as the average of the up direction of the headset and a fixed upward direction. This helps ensure that the hips are not leaning too far forward or backward.

To adjust the hip position when the player is bowing, we first calculate the angle between the forward direction of the headset and the downward direction. If the angle is greater than a specified threshold (`bowAngleThreshold`), we set the `isBowing` flag to true

